Bull,
Maybe you missed the recent flurry of e-mails over the memory topic.
That is my current focus ( but I loved finding 27 e-mails in my box
about computation time, goods everybody ).
My first impulse to your question is to say: don&#39;t stabalize!
Stabalizing is a method to destroy memory information by repeatedly
inputing the current state, and waiting until that input propigates the
network. So, yes, the network &quot;forgets&quot; previous states.
Allow the recurrent connections to be &#39;unstable.&#39; This may not seem
sane, but remember, you can assume a network will behave robustly when
you finish training it. If you train it to play a game, and memory has
an effect on it&#39;s fitness, you will most likely develop memory through
recurrent connections that don&#39;t behave well when you ask them to do
something else, like repeatedly giving it the same gamestate, which is
what stabalization does. Stabalization could be a usefull tool to
improve fitness in a game where for each arangment of the board, there
is one best next move. An example might be the little triangle pegboards
where you jump pegs until only one peg is left. Competitive games
usually don&#39;t have a single best move.

That&#39;s my take.
chad

